<h3 id="padua">Padua</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Scrovegni Chapel: One should definitely visit the Scrovegni Chapel while in Padua, but if time is short, make sure not to miss these two culinary gems.</li>
  <li>Mint coffee and Zabaione: Our journey continued to the beautiful city of Padua, where we savored a fragrant cup of mint coffee at Caffe Pedrocchi. And for dessert, the creamy and indulgent zabaione, like a sweet sonnet to the taste buds.</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="bologna">Bologna</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Tagliatelle al Ragu: Of course, we couldn‚Äôt pass through Bologna, known for its culinary heritage, without indulging in the iconic tagliatelle al ragu (what everyone else calls bolognese sauce). It‚Äôs like a warm hug from an Italian nonna.</li>
  <li>Leaning Towers: As we strolled through the city, we couldn‚Äôt help but notice Bologna‚Äôs leaning towers, one of them apparently even more inclined than the famous Pisa Tower. It seemed like Bologna was trying to out-lean Pisa in a friendly rivalry of tilting towers.</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="tuscany">Tuscany</h3>

<p><b>Florence:</b></p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Bistecca alla fiorentina</strong>: As we arrived in Florence, the birthplace of the Renaissance, we couldn‚Äôt resist the temptation of a succulent Bistecca alla fiorentina. It felt like a masterpiece for our palates, cooked to perfection, and seasoned with history.</li>
  <li>Sandwich with Olives, Provolone, and Prosciutto on Schiacciata: For a quick, yet delightful bite, we relished a sandwich filled with olives, provolone, and prosciutto between slices of schiacciata. It was like a Tuscan landscape painted with flavors.</li>
</ul>

